-->\n\n\t\t<!-- Ezoic - featured_1_mobile - under_page_title -->\n\t\t<span id="ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-111"></span><!-- placeholder 111 blocked.  Reason : no sizes -->\n\t\t<!-- End Ezoic - featured_1_mobile - under_page_title -->\n\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\n\n<div class="snopes-bt">\n\t<span id="5b22ddfa64-186-container"></span>\n</div>\n\n\n\t<div class="entry-content article-text">\n\n\t\t<div class="article-text-inner">\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class="section-break claim"><span>CLAIM</span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t<p>\n\t\t\t\t\tThe title of the David Crosby song "Page 43" is a reference to the New Testament.\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class="section-break"><span>RATING</span></h3>\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class="rating-wrapper">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<a class="claim false" href="https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/rating/false">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<img src="https://us-east-1.tchyn.io/snopes-production/uploads/2018/03/rating-false.png" />\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<span>False</span>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="snopes-partner-unit partner-unit-rating  adtester-container-640 adtester-container-641 active">\n\t<div class="snopes-partner-media ezpt_under_page_title">\n\n\t\t<!-- Ezoic - rating_1_desktop - under_page_title -->\n\t\t<span id="ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-640"></span>\n\t\t<!-- End Ezoic - rating_1_desktop - under_page_title -->\n\n\t\t<!-- Ezoic - rating_1_mobile - under_page_title -->\n\t\t<span id="ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-641"></span><!-- placeholder 641 blocked.  Reason : no sizes -->\n\t\t<!-- End Ezoic - rating_1_mobile - under_page_title -->\n\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<h3 class="section-break"><span>ORIGIN</span></h3>\n\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t<p>The 1988 film <i>Imagine: John Lennon</i> includes a scene in which a scruffy-looking young man is caught lurking on the grounds of John and Yoko\xe2\x80\x99s Tittenhurst Park estate in Ascot, England, and is brought to the masters of the house for questioning.  As John and Yoko stand in the doorway of their home inquiring about the lad\xe2\x80\x99s presence on their property, the interloper launches into a discussion about the meaning of lyrics to various Beatles songs, particularly \xe2\x80\x9cDig a Pony\xe2\x80\x9d (which was featured in the <i>Let It Be</i> movie and album).  </p><span id="ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-null" class="ezoic-adpicker-ad"></span><!-- placeholder  blocked.  Reason : inactive -->\n<p>John patiently explains to the youth that (like many of his songs) \xe2\x80\x9cDig a Pony\xe2\x80\x9d had no particular meaning \xe2\x80\x94 it was merely a collection of words and phrases that sounded good together, which listeners could imbue with whatever meaning(s) they chose to read into it.  John then sympathetically asks the young man if he\xe2\x80\x99s hungry and invites him in for a meal before sending him on his way:</p>\n<p><iframe width="560" height="315" under_second_paragraph -->\n\t\t<!-- Ezoic - content_body_1_mobile - under_second_paragraph -->\n\t\t<span id="ezoic-pub-ad-placeholder-650"></span><!-- placeholder 650 blocked.  Reason : no sizes -->\n\t\t<!-- End Ezoic - content_body_1_mobile - under_second_paragraph -->\n\n\t</div>\n</div>\n\n<p>That episode demonstrates a not uncommon phenomenon associated with popular music: Fans who are insistent they know exactly what a songwriter is referring to in a particular song, even when the title or lyric has no specific referent at all.  A case in point is the enigmatically titled <nobr>\xe2\x80\x9cPage 43,\xe2\x80\x9d</nobr> a David Crosby meditation on the theme of \xe2\x80\x9cdive into life before it passes you by\xe2\x80\x9d which appeared on the 1972 <i>Graham Nash/David Crosby</i> album:</p>\n<blockquote><p>\nLook around again<br />\nIt\xe2\x80\x99s the same old story<br />\nYou see, it\xe2\x80\x99s got to be<br />\nIt says right here on page 43<br />\nThat you should grab ahold of it<br />\nElse you\xe2\x80\x99ll find<br />\nIt\xe2\x80\x99s passed you by</p>\n<p>Rainbows all around<br />\nCan you find the silver and gold?<br />\nIt\xe2\x80\x99ll make you old<br />\nThe river can be hot or cold<br />\nAnd you should dive right into it<br />\nElse you\xe2\x80\x99ll find<br />\nIt\xe2\x80\x99s passed you by </p>\n<p>Pass it round one more time<br />\nI think I\xe2\x80\x99ll have a swallow of wine<br />\nLife is fine<br />\nEven with the ups and downs<br />\nAnd you should have a sip of it<br />\nElse you\xe2\x80\x99ll find<br />\nIt\xe2\x80\x99s passed you by.\n</p></blockquote>\n<p>The lyrics seem straightforward enough, but \xe2\x80\xa6 what is the <nobr>\xe2\x80\x9cpage 43\xe2\x80\x9d</nobr> from which they\xe2\x80\x99re supposedly drawn?  A page from a book?  Which one?</p>\n<p>In fact, as David Crosby acknowledged to interviewer Paul Zollo in 1993, <nobr>\xe2\x80\x9cpage 43\xe2\x80\x9d</nobr> didn\xe2\x80\x99t refer to anything definite at all \xe2\x80\x94 yet that didn\xe2\x80\x99t stop some listeners from declaring that they absolutely knew the answer:</p>\n<blockquote><p>\nQ: I wanted to ask you about \xe2\x80\x9cPage 43.\xe2\x80\x9d</p>\n<p>A: I wrote it in the main cabin of my boat in Sausalito. And it was under the influence, musically, of James Taylor.</p>\n<p>Q: It\xe2\x80\x99s a song about diving right into life.</p>\n<p>A: Yeah. Don\xe2\x80\x99t wait for it. Taste it. Go with it.</p>\n<p>Q: Was \xe2\x80\x9cPage 43\xe2\x80\x9d a page from a specific book?</p>\n<p>A: No. As a matter of fact, some very peculiar things happened with people saying [<i>in a low whisper</i>], <nobr>\xe2\x80\x9cPage 43.</nobr> Yeah. I read that too. I know that nobody else knows, but that was really far out.\xe2\x80\x9d [<i>Laughter</i>] And I\xe2\x80\x99m thinking, \xe2\x80\x9cYeah! What book are you thinking about?\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9cThe <i>Kaballah</i>!\xe2\x80\x9d [<i>Laughter</i>]  You have no idea which <nobr>page 43</nobr> they\xe2\x80\x99re absolutely sure that I\xe2\x80\x99m talking about. But they\xe2\x80\x99re sure.</p>\n<p>Q: One guy told me he was absolutely sure it was <nobr>page 43</nobr> of the New Testament.</p>\n<p>A: The New Testament. See, that\xe2\x80\x99s the one I didn\xe2\x80\x99t read. I read the Old Testament.  [<i>Laughs</i>] You know, Zap Comix, <nobr>Issue 28.</nobr> It could be <i>anything</i>. And they\xe2\x80\x99re <i>sure</i>. And they come up to you in a very conspiratorial way and say, <nobr>\xe2\x80\x9cPage 43,</nobr> yeah, I got it, man.\xe2\x80\x9d\n</p></blockquote>\n<p>We note for completeness\xe2\x80\x99 sake that different editions of the same book can be paginated differently, so even if one knew specifically which book <nobr>\xe2\x80\x9cPage 43\xe2\x80\x9d</nobr> referred to, that information wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t necessarily be sufficient to identify the material of interest.  Particularly in the case of a book such as the New Testament, which is available in many, many different versions and translations, a mere page number (rather than a chapter and verse citation) would be virtually useless as an identifier.</p>\n\n\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t\t\t<div class="social-share-footer">\n\t\t\t<a class="sumome-share-custom-footer" data-sumome-share-id="71f16955-7c9c-41bc-8746-e800ac59977d"></a>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class="article-footer-message">\n\t\t\t\t<p style="font-size: 20px;padding: 10px 0px 0px
